\f3\fs20 \cf0 For the first time, millennials and Generation Z have enough electoral clout to seriously compete with their elders. But many feel more disillusioned than empowered.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The oldest of them were just out of college on 9/11; the youngest were not yet born. Over the two decades that followed, they all came of age under storm clouds: of war, of recession, of mass shootings, wildfires and now a pandemic.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The result is perhaps the most profound generational gap since the 1960s: between the Generation X, baby boomer and Silent Generation voters who remember one world, and the millennial and Generation Z voters for whom that world never existed.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 In November, for the first time, the new generations will have enough electoral clout to seriously compete with the old. But, with Senator Bernie Sanders\'92s campaign barely clinging to life, many feel more disillusioned than empowered.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 In the Democratic primary race, most millennial and Gen Z voters \'97 meaning, roughly, people ages 18 to 39 \'97 have supported Mr. Sanders, of Vermont, or Senator Elizabeth Warren of Massachusetts, and few are enthusiastic about former Vice President Joseph R. Biden Jr. On the Republican side, young voters       \'a0    are less likely than older ones to support President Trump, and some conservatives have left the party altogether.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The problem is circular and self-reinforcing. Just when millennial and Gen Z voters have the most power to choose their leaders, many feel no one is speaking to them. So many of them don\'92t vote. So many candidates continue not to speak to them. So they get still more disillusioned.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 \'93I would love to see more emphasis on listening to young people and talking to us instead of at us,\'94 said Deana Ayers, 21, a senior at the University of North Texas who voted for Mr. Sanders. \'93I\'92m the future of your party. You should be giving me resources and training and listening to the way I want this party to look.\'94
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Within the Democratic Party, the generational tension has played out most vividly through the contest between Mr. Biden and Mr. Sanders. But it is fundamentally about young voters\'92 sense that they are living in an entirely different world than their parents, and that politicians \'97 or at least the ones winning elections \'97 aren\'92t acknowledging it.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Millions of millennials, born between 1981 and 1996, cast their first votes for Barack Obama, and members of Generation Z, born after 1996, began entering the electorate as Mr. Obama\'92s term was ending. For them, his administration is a reference point for who is electable and what is achievable.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 \'93We grew up with a black president who ran on a platform of change,\'94 said Michael May, 20, a student at the University of Toronto who voted for Ms. Warren in his home state, California. \'93We think that more is possible than older generations do.\'94
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 They also think more is needed \'97 and that, too, is a function of experience.
\f0\fs24 \

