\f3\fs20 \cf0 Some of the billionaire\'92s proposals wouldn\'92t be out of place for his more progressive presidential rivals.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Michael R. Bloomberg on Tuesday offered his proposals for regulating Wall Street, where he made his billions, promising a return of Obama-era oversight if elected president and invoking the name of one of his rivals, Senator Elizabeth Warren, in an attempt to connect with the Democratic Party\'92s progressive wing.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 As he proposed reversing some of President Trump\'92s deregulation of the finance industry, Mr. Bloomberg said he would rework the Volcker Rule, one of the most controversial regulations set up in the wake of the 2008 financial crisis. In the past, he has criticized the way the rule put limitations on how banks can invest their money.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Mr. Bloomberg, who will join the Democratic primary debate stage for the first time on Wednesday, also said he would increase the capital requirements at large financial institutions to head off the need for another taxpayer bailout, phase in a 0.1 percent tax on transactions like stock sales and curb overdraft fees that hit the financially vulnerable.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Perhaps the most surprising proposal, given Mr. Bloomberg\'92s close personal ties to business titans, is a plan for the Justice Department to create a team to fight corporate crime by \'93encouraging prosecutors to pursue individuals, not only corporations, for infractions.\'94
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 \'93The financial system isn\'92t working the way it should for most Americans,\'94 Mr. Bloomberg said in a statement. \'93The stock market is at an all-time high, but almost all of the gains are going to a small number of people.\'94
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Some of the proposals offered by Mr. Bloomberg \'97 a former Salomon Brothers trader whose estimated $63 billion fortune came from selling data to Wall Street \'97 suggest how far to the left the moderate Democratic presidential hopefuls have felt they need to tack.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 He shares his transaction tax proposal with three fellow candidates, Ms. Warren, Senator Bernie Sanders of Vermont and Pete Buttigieg, the former mayor of South Bend, Ind. Representative Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez, an outspoken progressive from New York, last year co-sponsored a bill that called for such a tax.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 By releasing a plan that contains provisions that Wall Street may balk at, Mr. Bloomberg is trying to confront one of his biggest liabilities as a candidate. In its polling and research, his campaign has found that Americans know little about him beyond two facts: He is a former mayor of New York and a billionaire.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Mr. Bloomberg and his strategists have used various tactics to stress the parts of his biography that help soften his image. His ads describe his middle-class upbringing in Boston and highlight his philanthropic giving, for instance.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 He has also started talking more often about his plan to raise $5 trillion in new tax revenue from high earners and corporations. His message to voters as he campaigns across the country has been, in essence, that the government should raise taxes on people like him because they can afford it.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The surcharge on trading, meant to raise money for social programs like expanded health care coverage, has been roundly criticized by the sort of pro-business groups that Mr. Bloomberg had long been sympathetic to, like the U.S. Chamber of Commerce.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The group immediately criticized the proposal. A transaction tax \'93hits Main Street, not Wall Street,\'94 said Tom Quaadman, a chamber executive. He added that it would \'93increase the cost of capital, decrease investment, harm businesses and hurt Americans who are saving and investing.\'94
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Rachel Nagler, a Bloomberg campaign spokeswoman, argued that such a tax \'93is an effective and relatively painless way to raise more tax revenue from the wealthy,\'94 citing its use in Britain and Hong Kong. A 2018 analysis by Congress\'92s Joint Committee on Taxation estimated that a tax similar to the one proposed by Mr. Bloomberg would raise $777 billion over 10 years.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Mr. Bloomberg\'92s plan embraces many of the regulatory changes made in the years after the financial crisis, even though he has often argued that rules aimed at reforming Wall Street are bad for the economy. In 2010, Mr. Bloomberg urged Democratic lawmakers not to get too tough on the finance industry, and he criticized the Volcker Rule, which is meant to reduce speculative trading by banks. He called the proposed restrictions \'93shortsighted,\'94 with the potential to reduce middle-class jobs.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 On Tuesday, Mr. Bloomberg said he would toughen the Volcker Rule \'97 although his idea is more like a major rewrite. It would assume that banks were engaging in safe practices as long as they didn\'92t gain or lose too much on a deal. Rather than getting in traders\'92 heads about what constitutes a speculative trade, he proposes taxing big gains and losses, reasoning that volatile outcomes beyond a certain threshold must be the result of overly speculative activity.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Ms. Nagler rejected the notion that Mr. Bloomberg was flip-flopping.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 \'93Context matters,\'94 she said. When the Volcker Rule was introduced, Mr. Bloomberg \'93was skeptical of regulators\'92 ability to divine traders\'92 intent,\'94 which was how the law required regulators to judge investments, she added. Mr. Bloomberg\'92s new plan would focus \'93on the outcome of speculative trading \'97 big gains and losses \'97 rather than on traders\'92 intent.\'94
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Isaac Boltansky, director of policy research at Compass Point Research and Trading, said Mr. Bloomberg was engaging in \'93relatively tough talk\'94 on banks and taking positions that were \'93more politically progressive than originally expected.\'94
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 \'93But we caution that talking about altering the Volcker Rule is exponentially simpler than actually revising the rule,\'94 Mr. Boltansky wrote in a note to investors.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Mr. Bloomberg has faced escalating attacks by his fellow Democrats as he rises in the polls. His rivals, most notably Mr. Sanders, have made his wealth an issue by repeatedly accusing him of trying \'93to buy the election\'94 with an advertising budget that is already approaching $500 million after less than three months. 
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Mr. Bloomberg\'92s immense wealth is a thorny matter in other ways: He owns a financial information and news behemoth that has said it will not do in-depth investigations of him or any other Democrats running for president. On Tuesday, Tim O\'92Brien, a senior adviser to the Bloomberg campaign, said Mr. Bloomberg would sell his company if he was elected \'97 although he would not sell to a foreign buyer or private equity.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Although Mr. Bloomberg\'92s proposal frequently name-checked President Barack Obama, he also referred to Ms. Warren. He said he would strengthen the Consumer Financial Protection Bureau, and pointed out it was established under her leadership. Mr. Bloomberg said he would reverse some rule changes made by Mr. Trump and expand the agency\'92s power over auto lending and credit reporting.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Some of his proposals were thin on specifics. For example, the consumer bureau already oversees auto loans made by banks but not by car dealers \'97 who aren\'92t specifically mentioned in Mr. Bloomberg\'92s plan. A person familiar with the proposal said that the proposal was indeed meant to include dealers and that they had been left out unintentionally.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 \'93The devil is in the details,\'94 said Dennis Kelleher, the president of the group Better Markets, which advocates rules that would rein in Wall Street and protect consumers.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 But Mr. Kelleher said he believed Mr. Bloomberg was moving in the right direction on important issues. \'93He\'92s indicating that he disagrees with Trump\'92s deregulation, and he\'92s indicating that he\'92s going to be much tougher in a bunch of areas,\'94 Mr. Kelleher said.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Opponents of regulation swiftly condemned Mr. Bloomberg\'92s proposals.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 \'93His plan would slow down growth, innovation and entrepreneurship in the country,\'94 said Veronique de Rugy, a senior research fellow at the Mercatus Center at George Mason University.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 In recent days, Mr. Bloomberg has been forced to defend his past comments on financial regulations. In 2011, for instance, he said: \'93It was not the banks that created the mortgage crisis. It was, plain and simple, Congress who forced everybody to go and give mortgages to people who were on the cusp.\'94
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Mr. Bloomberg said he would bolster or restore elements of the 2010 Dodd-Frank law that were reversed or reduced under Mr. Trump. For example, he proposes making stress tests for banks more stringent and reinstating the requirement that banks produce annual \'93living wills,\'94 which are complex documents that detail how they would unwind their operations in a bankruptcy.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Elsewhere in his plan, Mr. Bloomberg said he would merge Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac, two government-owned housing giants. He would strengthen consumer protections that govern payday lending and financial advisers, and automatically enroll student-loan borrowers into income-based repayment plans with payments capped at 5 percent of disposable income.
\f0\fs24 \

