\f3\fs20 \cf0 The issue is getting more attention than it has in decades, except from the Democratic front-runner.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 In her parting remarks to her staff this week, Elizabeth Warren took a moment to talk about the lasting mark her candidacy had left on the race. \'93You know, a year ago, people weren\'92t talking about a two-cent wealth tax, universal child care, canceling student loan debt for 43 million Americans while reducing the racial wealth gap or breaking up big tech,\'94 she said. \'93And now they are.\'94
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 She\'92s right \'97 particularly about child care. Ms. Warren led the pack by putting out a groundbreaking proposal for public child care last February; Bernie Sanders and Pete Buttigieg eventually followed suit. Three candidates with universal child care plans may not sound like all that much \'97 but consider that before this race, no major candidate running for the White House had mentioned universal child care since the 1970s. That three top-tier contenders had competing plans demonstrates that this issue is an increasingly salient one for American voters. Child care is also an increasingly dire crisis facing the country \'97 one that demands an equally aggressive response.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Of course, two of those contenders have left the race; the Democratic primary has essentially narrowed to a two-man contest between Mr. Sanders and Joe Biden. But where is Mr. Biden\'92s plan for how to address the broken child care system American families face? Without one, he risks being out of step with this historic moment.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 It wasn\'92t so long ago that the notion of not just universal child care but publicly run universal child care was downright mainstream. The United States has had such a system in place before: During World War II, as men were shipped off to fight abroad and women were called to work in factories, President Franklin Roosevelt funneled funding from a wartime infrastructure bill to creating and running a network of child care centers. They cost about $10 a day in today\'92s dollars for 12 hours of care year round, and the quality was high.       \'a0    They attracted qualified, trained teachers and had low child-to-teacher ratios.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Mothers loved them. In exit interviews in California, women gave them a nearly 100 percent satisfaction rating. They also improved children\'92s education,       \'a0    employment and earnings later in life, while increasing how much their mothers were able to work. But while child advocates lobbied to keep the program in place after the war, President Harry Truman shut it down as soon as Japan surrendered.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The idea of enacting a federally funded universal child care system didn\'92t disappear, however, and it nearly became a fixture of American life in the 1970s. As more women entered the paid work force, and research started to coalesce around the importance of early education for children\'92s development, Congress drafted legislation in the late 1960s that would create a federally funded but locally administered network of child care centers.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 It was a bipartisan initiative, one that, at first, President Richard Nixon seemed to support. He himself had called for\'93a national commitment to providing all American children an opportunity for healthful and stimulating development during the first five years of life.\'94 The legislation passed in 1971.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Then Nixon did a 180 at the behest of his special assistant Pat Buchanan, who told me in 2014, \'93My view back then was that it was philosophically out of the question for the Nixon administration to support a major new welfare program.\'94 Nixon issued       \'a0    a scathing veto that called it \'93family-weakening\'94 and \'93truly a long leap into the dark for the United States government,\'94 comparing it to communism.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The toxicity of his words infected the debate over child care for decades \'97 and helped bury the history of public child care in America. The 1980s and \'9290s were consumed with stories of satanic rituals at day cares and       \'a0    studies claiming that child care would ruin children. Even as recently as 2016, the Republican Party platform       \'a0    initially opposed universal preschool because it \'93inserts the state in the family relationship in the very early stages of a child\'92s life.\'94
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 But it\'92s an issue that policymakers can no longer afford to ignore. The cost of child care has increased nearly exponentially in recent decades, far outpacing inflation. Now       \'a0    it consumes more of the average family\'92s budget than health care, transportation or food, and in most places it rivals housing, too. Full-time center care often       \'a0    costs more than tuition and fees for public college. That money still doesn\'92t buy quality, though. A 2006 survey found that       \'a0    fewer than 10 percent of American day care centers provided high-quality care. And that\'92s for the families lucky enough to get their child a spot:       \'a0    More than half of Americans live in a neighborhood without enough child care seats for all the children who need them.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Even the Democratic presidential hopefuls who didn\'92t release plans as detailed and bold as Ms. Warren\'92s or Mr. Sanders\'92s talked about child care. Amy Klobuchar sponsored the Child Care for Working Families Act, a Democratic proposal in Congress with similar aims of universal coverage. Mike Bloomberg\'92s early-education plan supported higher-quality and lower-cost child care and universal preschool. Even President Trump has talked about child care,       \'a0    proposing on the campaign trail to increase tax deductions to cover the cost and       \'a0    calling for a one-time $1 billion investment in his White House budget.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 This is a vast, complicated crisis that is dampening our entire economy. It makes sense for presidential hopefuls to put forward ideas that are bold enough to match the stakes.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 But so far, although Mr. Biden has supported universal preschool in the past, he has been more or less silent on what parents of younger children should do. And while today he supports an increased child tax credit that can help families cover the cost, he wrote an op-ed article in 1981 arguing that the credit subsidizes the \'93deterioration of the family\'94 and \'93encourages a couple\'94 to \'93evade full responsibility for their children\'94 by helping them put those children in day care. The article argued against any universal government child care assistance because it would go to well-to-do families, but it also repeated language from Republicans who fearmongered about child care.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The best way for Mr. Biden to disavow any antiquated positions and to assure voters that he is in tune with their most pressing needs would be to release his own universal child care plan. He doesn\'92t have to reinvent the wheel; he can simply look back at our own history and take inspiration from what we would have had if things had gone slightly differently.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Better late than never.
