\f3\fs20 This article is part of the Debatable newsletter. You can sign up here to receive it Tuesdays and Thursdays.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 \'93This is a very dangerous moment for the Democratic Party,\'94 Van Jones said on CNN Tuesday. \'93You now have an insurgency that\'92s about to be defeated. What do you do with the people that you defeat?"
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 It\'92s a question that looms over the close of every party primary, when warring factions are called upon to unite in the face of a general election, but especially this one: Only about half of Bernie Sanders\'92s supporters in one January poll said they would certainly vote for the Democratic nominee.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 So if Joe Biden does win the nomination, as seems likely, what will he need to do to rally the Democratic Party and avoid losing to President Trump?
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 \'91Biden is winning the primary but losing his party\'92s future\'92
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The primaries have made clear that Mr. Biden has a problem with younger voters, a key part of the Obama coalition, as Evan Halper and Janet Hook have       \'a0    reported for The Los Angeles Times. \'93Many young Democrats believe the political and economic system isn\'92t working for them and want candidates who will shake things up, as many polls have shown,\'94 they write. So far, Mr. Biden does not appear to be that candidate: On Super Tuesday, he drew just 17 percent of voters under 45, according to exit polls. This week\'92s primaries revealed a similarly stark generational schism, with younger voters       \'a0    overwhelmingly flocking to Mr. Sanders. The journalist Mehdi Hasan tweeted:
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Adopting parts of Mr. Sanders\'92s platform would help Mr. Biden with both younger, more left-leaning voters and moderates, Eric Levitz writes at New York magazine. Revising his conservative stance on marijuana is an obvious concession he should make, Mr. Levitz says, since legalization is popular both generally and among key Electoral College constituencies. Other parts of Mr. Sanders\'92s platform with broad support include a wealth tax, worker representation on corporate boards, free public college tuition, and a 15 percent cap on credit-card interest rates.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 [Related: \'93The Green New Deal Is the Answer to Joe Biden\'92s Problems\'94]
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Mr. Biden also needs to adopt a more receptive attitude toward young progressives, according to Mr. Jones. \'93You\'92ve got young people who are graduating with a quarter-million dollars in debt, you\'92ve got young people with a lot of pain, and they had a champion\'94 in Mr. Sanders. In contrast, Mr. Biden has said he has \'93no empathy\'94 for \'93the younger generation.\'94
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 \'93Vice President Biden should have just as much responsibility as the Sanders folks are asked to have around bringing the party together and really being unified,\'94 Mar\'eda Urbina, the political director of the liberal political organization Indivisible, said on MSNBC. \'93And in order to do that, there has to be a little more digging and listening\'94 to the party\'92s left wing. To some degree, Michelle Cottle       \'a0    writes in The Times, Mr. Biden is showing signs of doing so.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 \'91Biden needs to say now who\'92ll be in his White House\'92
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Mr. Biden needs to think carefully about his vice-presidential pick, says the Times columnist Frank Bruni. For one thing, he\'92s 77 years old, and would be 78 upon inauguration, so voters may care even more than usual about the other name on the ticket. But also, \'93Biden\'92s message is competence, experience and normalcy,\'94 Mr. Bruni writes. \'93The Democratic vice-presidential nominee must reflect that. If that nominee is a woman, a person of color or both, all the better.\'94
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Mr. Biden should also announce picks for his cabinet, Will Bunch argues at The Philadelphia Inquirer.       \'a0    Suspicion already abounds among young progressives that he might fill his administration with \'93Wall Street hacks.\'94 The solution, Mr. Bunch says, is to announce a team that signals \'93a better normal\'94 (with Gov. Jay Inslee in charge of climate policy or the Environmental Protection Agency, for example). \'93The emphasis ought to be not just on competence \'97 reminding voters that the grown-ups will be in charge after four years of Trump \'97 but also to show young people that even if Biden isn\'92t a card-carrying leftist, his presidency would still be the most progressive one in modern U.S. history,\'94 Mr. Bunch writes.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 \'91It may not matter how much enthusiasm Biden generates\'92
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Mr. Biden\'92s lack of appeal among young progressives won\'92t matter in the general election, writes Jon Healey, the deputy editorial page editor at The Los Angeles Times. He argues that\'92s because many such voters sat out the 2016 election for fear that Hillary Clinton and Mr. Trump were \'93two sides of the same coin.\'94 But three years into this administration, \'93no one can reasonably see even as solidly establishment a figure as Biden as interchangeable with Trump,\'94 Mr. Healey writes.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Nor is Biden as uniquely disliked as Hillary Clinton was, according to Ann Coulter. \'93After slaughtering Hillary in Michigan four years ago, Bernie was blown away by Biden last night,\'94 she said. \'93Conclusion: In 2016, Trump got to run against a massively unpopular candidate.\'94 The writer Gary Legum tweeted:
\f0\fs24 \

