\f3\fs20 \cf0 Sunday\'92s debate will be the first one-on-one matchup between Joseph R. Biden Jr. and Bernie Sanders. So, how do they actually compare on policy?
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Former Vice President Joseph R. Biden Jr. and Senator       \'a0    Bernie Sanders of Vermont will debate one on one for the first time on Sunday, and Mr. Sanders, who is staying in the Democratic primary race       \'a0    despite a series of defeats, has already telegraphed his strategy.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 \'93Joe, what are you going to do?\'94 Mr. Sanders repeatedly asked at a news conference last week, ticking off a laundry list of issues he plans to press Mr. Biden on, including health care, student debt, climate change, mass incarceration, immigration and wealth inequality.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Mr. Biden, for his part, has criticized Mr. Sanders on gun control and on his signature policy proposal, \'93Medicare for all.\'94
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Here is where the two candidates stand on some of the issues each may raise.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Health care
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Biden
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 One of the biggest distinctions between the candidates is that Mr. Biden does not support a universal government-run health insurance program like \'93Medicare for all.\'94 Instead, he supports maintaining the private insurance system but adding a Medicare-like public option that anyone could sign up for \'97 a proposal that still goes well beyond the Affordable Care Act. He estimates       \'a0    his plan would cost $750 billion over a decade.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Mr. Biden would also increase tax credits for people to buy insurance through the Affordable Care Act marketplace. His plan doesn\'92t specifically address medical debt.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Sanders
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 One of the bedrock principles of Mr. Sanders\'92s campaign is that health care is a human right, and he is the torchbearer for Medicare for all. He estimates his plan would cost       \'a0    about $30 trillion over 10 years and would be paid for by new revenue of about $17.5 trillion, along with \'93current federal, state and local government spending.\'94
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 He also wants to eliminate $81 billion in medical debt.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Coronavirus
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Biden
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The new coronavirus has quickly become the most urgent problem facing the country, and Mr. Biden released       \'a0    a plan on Thursday calling for free testing, \'93the elimination of all cost barriers to preventive care and treatment for Covid-19,\'94 and emergency paid leave for affected workers.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 He also wants to restore a White House office that oversaw responses to global health crises \'97 an office that the Obama administration created and the Trump administration eliminated \'97 and direct the Justice Department to combat price gouging for medical supplies.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Sanders
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Mr. Sanders outlined his plan to address the coronavirus in a speech on Thursday. He called for a national state of emergency (which President Trump subsequently declared), emergency funding for paid sick leave, an expansion of community health centers and a mandate that all medications related to coronavirus be sold at cost.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Student debt
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Biden
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Mr. Biden wants to make two-year community colleges and \'93other high-quality training programs\'94 debt-free, but would not cancel existing student debt the way Mr. Sanders is proposing. His plan would, however, forgive the remaining balance for people who paid 5 percent of their discretionary income (with the first $25,000 exempt) toward their loans for 20 years.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Sanders
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Mr. Sanders wants to make all public colleges and universities free,       \'a0    cancel all student loan debt \'97 about $1.6 trillion owed by about 45 million Americans \'97 and cap student loan interest rates at 1.88 percent. He says he would pay for the debt cancellation with a tax on financial transactions like stock trades.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Climate change
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Biden
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Mr. Biden\'92s $1.7 trillion climate plan calls for 100 percent carbon-free energy and       \'a0    net-zero carbon emissions by 2050. It would end fossil fuel subsidies and subsidize clean energy, but envisions a continued role for fossil fuels for some time: It would not ban fracking, for instance. Mr. Biden also supports federal funding for carbon capture and sequestration programs that could, in theory, eventually offset some emissions.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Sanders
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Mr. Sanders is a proponent of the Green New Deal, a sweeping resolution that calls for aggressive action to combat climate change, and has modeled his $16.3 trillion proposal on that plan. He calls for an immediate ban on fracking, for the electricity and transportation sectors to be carbon-free by 2030, and for the United States to       \'a0    end the use of fossil fuels no later than 2050.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Immigration
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Biden
\f0\fs24 \

