\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Sanders
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Mr. Sanders, like Mr. Biden, supports an assault weapons ban, a voluntary buyback program and many other gun restrictions. But much like criminal justice for Mr. Biden, gun control is a difficult area for Mr. Sanders, politically speaking: Earlier in his career, he voted against federal background checks and legal liability for gun manufacturers.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Abortion
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Biden
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Mr. Biden has a long and complicated record on abortion. In the 1980s, he supported an attempt to let states overturn Roe v. Wade, and he supported the Hyde Amendment \'97 which prevents Medicaid from covering abortion in most circumstances \'97       \'a0    until just last year.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Today, however, he supports the same basic set of policies every major Democrat in the race did, including legislation to codify Roe v. Wade, repeals of the Hyde Amendment and the global and domestic \'93gag rules,\'94 and a pledge to nominate only Supreme Court justices who support abortion rights.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Sanders
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Mr. Sanders also supports legislation to codify Roe v. Wade, opposes the Hyde Amendment and the global and domestic gag rules, and has promised to nominate only Supreme Court justices who would uphold Roe v. Wade.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Homelessness
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Biden
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Mr. Biden is proposing $640 billion over 10 years for affordable housing, as well as a \'93bill of rights\'94 that would provide protections against eviction, foreclosure and predatory mortgages. He also wants to create tax credits for renters and first-time homeowners and expand the Section 8 housing voucher program.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Sanders
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Mr. Sanders proposes spending $2.5 trillion to build about 10 million permanently affordable housing units. He also wants to implement a national rent control standard and spend $70 billion to repair public housing.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Money in politics
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Biden
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Mr. Biden is calling for a constitutional amendment to make elections completely publicly funded, eliminating all private contributions \'97 a significant step beyond what Mr. Sanders has proposed. In the shorter term, he wants to put new restrictions on super PACs and publicly finance major parties\'92 national conventions.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Sanders
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Like most Democrats, Mr. Sanders wants to overturn Citizens United \'97 the Supreme Court decision that prevents the government from banning political spending by corporations in elections \'97 and then pass a constitutional amendment that makes clear that money is not speech. He also wants to       \'a0    abolish super PACs and has called for a ban on corporate contributions to the Democratic National Convention.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 He has criticized Mr. Biden for accepting campaign contributions from billionaires.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Wealth inequality
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Biden
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Mr. Biden wants to strengthen collective bargaining, hold corporate executives personally liable for anti-union efforts and enforce labor laws more strongly. He is also calling, like many Democrats, for a $15 minimum wage, and for higher taxes on corporations and wealthy investors.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Sanders
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Mr. Sanders has suggested taxing the rich with a wealth tax and       \'a0    progressive estate tax while also       \'a0    enacting a federal jobs guarantee,       \'a0    doubling union membership and taking other steps to bolster the working and middle class. He also wants to       \'a0    break up big banks.
