\f3\fs20 \cf0 Bernie Sanders, Elizabeth Warren and Pete Buttigieg are trying to woo older black voters with policy. Those policies may be why they\'92re struggling to win their support.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 DANVILLE, Va. \'97 Ten minutes into a small community meeting between black farmers from Southern Virginia and regional campaign staff for Senator Elizabeth Warren of Massachusetts, an aide took the floor.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 He was the only white person to speak in a room of older black voters seated in an old beauty salon. He stood, delivering an off-the-cuff pitch for Ms. Warren\'92s plan to help rural black America: proposals for new access to funding for black farmers, and to address discrimination in the United States Department of Agriculture. She understood the challenges black farmers faced, he said.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 But he was cut off midsentence, before he could finish his appeal for their support. Instead, the black farmers had a message for him, and for Ms. Warren\'92s campaign. Plans and rhetoric are one thing, but to trust a candidate to deliver \'97 or the government at all \'97 is entirely another.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 In a community all too familiar with legal discrimination and unequal access to public services, believing in \'93big, structural change,\'94 as Ms. Warren likes to call it, is a gamble.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 \'93No disrespect,\'94 called out Lauren Hudson, a 62-year-old hemp farmer, \'93but there\'92s a whole different avenue when we go for funding versus when a white family goes for funding.\'94
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Democratic candidates have come to understand that they need policies that target racial inequities, especially to win over black voters \'97 a vital force in the Democratic primary. Senator Bernie Sanders of Vermont says single-payer health insurance will close disparities like the higher infant mortality rate in black families. Former Mayor       \'a0    Pete Buttigieg of South Bend, Ind., released his Frederick Douglass Plan, which calls for overhauling the criminal justice system, health care equity, and education funding.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 In addition to her proposals for black farmers, Ms. Warren has aimed to design her health care and education plans so that they take corrective steps to address historical inequality.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Still, even as the plans add up, black voters have largely not shown enthusiasm about these candidates, and the polling numbers have barely budged. According to a recent nationwide poll of black voters from The Washington Post and Ipsos, former Vice President       \'a0    Joseph R. Biden Jr. holds a significant edge, with the support of nearly 50 percent of respondents. Among black voters 65 and older, poll showed Mr. Biden ahead by 60 percentage points.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Mr. Sanders had 20 percent support, driven largely by his popularity with black voters under 35 years old. Ms. Warren was third in The Post\'92s poll, with 9 percent.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Over the course of her campaign, at events geared toward black voters, Ms. Warren often cites policy proposals such as investment in historically black colleges and new housing in formerly redlined communities. Crowds generally respond positively.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 \'93I want a world where the color of your skin doesn\'92t matter, you get the same opportunities,\'94 Ms. Warren said at an event over the weekend hosted with groups including the Iowa chapter of the N.A.A.C.P. \'93We do not fix a system like this by pretending that race doesn\'92t matter.\'94
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Mr. Sanders\'92s progress with black voters has been a mixed bag; he is beloved among younger voters and viewed with some suspicion by older ones, who largely supported Hillary Clinton in 2016 and found his insurgent campaign to be harmful to her in the general election. Late last year, Mr. Sanders replaced his South Carolina state director, a sign of the campaign\'92s desire to shift his strategy for winning over black voters.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Mr. Biden\'92s candidacy is helped by several factors, including his widespread name recognition, public proximity to former President Barack Obama, and close relationship with black community leaders dating to his years in the Senate.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 But in interviews with dozens of black voters in Virginia and South Carolina, another theme emerges: Mr. Biden is also ahead because his leading rivals have yet to wrestle with how their promises of structural change must overcome historical distrust of the government in black communities.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Theodore Johnson, a senior fellow at the Brennan Center for Justice who studies race and electoral politics, said black skepticism in government stretches back decades, citing Booker T. Washington and his late 19th century and early 20th century argument for black self-help, rather than a focus on systemic discrimination. Black voters are often described as \'93moderates,\'94 but Mr. Johnson said the voting choices are more nuanced than straightforward ideological choices.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Racism \'93contributes to black people\'92s lack of support for mass federal programs,\'94 Mr. Johnson said. \'93There\'92s a sense that, if you prefer federal programs, that can be an admission that you can\'92t make it without white people or government.\'94
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 In \'93Medicare for all,\'94 free college and other signature progressive proposals, like the cancellation of student loan debt or housing equality, candidates are asking black voters to trust that government can correct the same systemic inequalities that government helped create. But there is often no plan to undo the cynicism that decades of governmental failure have created among older black voters in particular.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 \'93No matter who is in office, the government has not been our best friend,\'94 said Samuel Crisp, 73. He is part of the Piedmont Progressive Farmers Group, which focuses on egg production, and attended the Warren campaign event in Virginia.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 \'93They all have programs that work against us,\'94 he added. \'93And they don\'92t seem to understand that.\'94
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 There is some precedent for selling older black voters on the promise for structural change. In 2004, the populist campaign of Senator John Edwards of North Carolina won the South Carolina Democratic primary contest. The Rev. Jesse Jackson\'92s presidential campaigns in 1984 and 1988 succeeded in bringing a message of systemic upheaval to black voters \'97 winning 11 contests in 1988, including in Virginia and South Carolina. In an interview, Mr. Jackson urged the current crop of left-wing candidates like Mr. Sanders and Ms. Warren to get better at working to relate to and understand black communities.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 \'93I earned the trust of the people. I worked with them on the ground. I wasn\'92t just an election candidate. I served with them,\'94 Mr. Jackson said. \'93I was at their restaurants. I played football. I stayed in their homes.\'94
\f0\fs24 \

