\f3\fs20 T-Mobile and Sprint finally make a connection
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 A federal judge is expected to approve      \'a0    T-Mobile\'92s $26 billion takeover of Sprint, perhaps even today, bringing a yearslong merger campaign to an end.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The winners:
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20  SoftBank, which pumped billions of dollars into Sprint over nearly a decade. The T-Mobile deal turned out to be its best hope of rescuing an expensive bad bet.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20  Bankers from nearly a dozen firms working on the transaction. Deep breath: PJT Partners, Deutsche Bank, Evercore, Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley for T-Mobile; Raine, Centerview, Citigroup and JPMorgan Chase for Sprint; and Mizuho and SMBC Nikko for SoftBank. They could split fees of at least $155 million, according to the consultancy Freeman &amp; Company.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20  Makan Delrahim, the Justice Department\'92s antitrust chief, who helped save the deal from regulatory limbo \'97 then complained about states\'92 efforts to unwind his work.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The losers: 
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20  State attorneys general, who sought to block the deal despite its approval by the Trump administration, including those of California and New York. They argued that it would lead to a loss of competition and higher prices for consumers.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The great unknown:
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20  Consumers, who may not feel the effects of the deal for years, for good or bad.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Trump\'92s budget sends a message
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The White House\'92s $4.8 trillion budget proposal features \'93a familiar list of deep cuts to student loan assistance, affordable housing efforts, food stamps and Medicaid,\'94 the NYT reports. It lifts spending on defense and the border wall, and extends individual tax cuts set to expire in 2025.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 It won\'92t happen. Or, at least, it\'92s unlikely to be approved by Congress in its entirety. Instead, the budget largely serves to signal the administration\'92s priorities ahead of its re-election campaign.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 It relies on rosy economic assumptions to make the numbers work, with punchy forecasts for G.D.P. growth and government borrowing costs leading to a steady reduction in the deficit and, eventually, a balanced budget by 2035. It\'92s common practice, of course, for administrations to publish overly optimistic forecasts alongside its policy proposals.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 On the financial front, the budget cuts support for student-loan relief programs and       \'a0    reduces funding for the Consumer Financial Protection Bureau. There\'92s a small increase for the Treasury Department\'92s Financial Crimes Enforcement Network, intended to help combat \'93emerging virtual currency and cybercrime threats.\'94
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The fine print: Politico runs down the quirkier aspects of the budget, including the reveal of a new paint job for Air Force One, flagged by the president       \'a0    with much fanfare over the summer. 
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Amazon looks to question Trump in cloud-computing case
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The tech giant isn\'92t letting up in its legal battle over the Pentagon\'92s cloud-computing contract, which the Trump administration awarded to Microsoft last year. Amazon wants President Trump and Defense Secretary Mark Esper to give depositions, reports Karen Weise of the NYT.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 A recap: Amazon has argued that Mr. Trump let personal animus against its founder Jeff Bezos \'97 driven largely by coverage from the WaPo, which Mr. Bezos owns \'97 affect an important decision for American national security.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Amazon cited tweets and other public comments by Mr. Trump in its court filing seeking to depose the president. What it doesn\'92t do is provide direct evidence that Mr. Trump directed Mr. Esper to blackball Amazon.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Both Microsoft and the Pentagon oppose the deposition request. The Defense Department called it \'93unnecessary, burdensome and merely seeks to delay getting this important technology into the hands of our warfighters.\'94
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Reality check: Courts don\'92t automatically grant these kinds of requests, the WSJ notes \'97 and deposing cabinet-level officials is relatively rare.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 That huge Slack deal? It wasn\'92t what you thought.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Shares in Slack jumped yesterday after Business Insider reported that IBM would use the workplace messaging app for all its employees \'97 and then promptly gave up the gains after Slack clarified what the deal meant.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Here\'92s what happened:
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20  The big news was that all of IBM\'92s 350,000 employees would use the messaging app, a victory for Slack over rivals like Microsoft\'92s Teams service.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20  Business Insider erroneously reported that the deal would make IBM Slack\'92s biggest customer, sending the messaging company\'92s shares up as much as 15 percent.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20  Some investors even speculated that IBM would try to buy Slack outright.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20  Slack then published a regulatory filing clarifying that IBM was already its biggest customer, and that the new deal wouldn\'92t meaningfully change its financial guidance.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Shares in Slack fell 7 percent in after-hours trading.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 U.S. blames the Chinese military for Equifax breach
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 If you thought relations between Washington and Beijing had thawed after the recent trade deal breakthrough, think again.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Federal prosecutors yesterday charged four Chinese military officers with hacking into Equifax in 2017, stealing trade secrets and the personal data of 145 million Americans. It was only the second time that the Justice Department had indicted the Chinese military on suspicions of hacking.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The charges show that the Trump administration remains worried about a Chinese threat to U.S. national security:
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20  Attorney General Bill Barr said yesterday that China could use the stolen personal information and combine it with A.I. to target American officials.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20  He pointed to previous cyberattacks that he said had been orchestrated by Beijing, including those affecting the health insurer Anthem and the hotel chain Marriott.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20  Last week, Mr. Barr suggested that the U.S. government finance takeovers of European telecoms to counter the rise of the Chinese tech firm Huawei.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Expect the Trump administration to keep up the carrot-and-stick approach with Beijing as it negotiates the second phase of a trade deal.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Brandless\'92s failure isn\'92t the end of the world for SoftBank
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The direct-to-consumer retailer said yesterday that it was shutting down, a first for a portfolio company in SoftBank\'92s $100 billion Vision Fund. But it\'92s not exactly a huge disaster for Masa Son\'92s tech conglomerate.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 SoftBank had invested $100 million in Brandless, which sold inexpensive household and food items, such as \'93dog shampoo and conditioner,\'94 for $3 each. Last year, SoftBank executives reportedly pushed the company to turn a profit. (Imagine that.)
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Brandless blamed a \'93fiercely competitive\'94 retail market for its collapse. But it had also gone through a carousel of management changes and tried raising prices for some products. And it had tried pivoting to trendier things like CBD oil.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 It\'92s the latest bit of bad news for SoftBank, after other Vision Fund portfolio companies \'97 like the robot pizza company Zume \'97 announced layoffs. News reports have also suggested that it was struggling to raise money for a second Vision Fund.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Andrew\'92s take: The headlines suggest that Brandless is another example of trouble for SoftBank. In truth, Brandless is basically lint in Vision Fund\'92s wallet pocket.
