\f3\fs20 Investors shrug off Trump impeachment
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Voting nearly along party lines, the House approved two articles of impeachmentagainst President Trump, making him the third president in history to face removal by the Senate. But the stock market has been largely unfazed by the news of impeachment proceedings, and       \'a0    that is unlikely to change, reports MarketWatch.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Investors are shrugging at the news because they don\'92t expect the Republican-controlled Senate to remove the president from office.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Market participants have grown more comfortable with the expectation that Mr. Trump would be impeached but not convicted, according to an investor survey conducted by RBC Capital Markets.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 \'93Perhaps the most relevant concern for investors is whether the impeachment damages Trump\'92s prospects in 2020,\'94 MarketWatch reported. \'93Some analysts contend the impeachment is more likely to benefit Trump.\'94
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 A strong economy supports investors\'92 sentiments:
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20  \'93Investors look at fundamentals \'97 economic growth, earnings, labor costs and so forth \'97 and none of these factors have been affected by impeachment, \'94 the C.I.O. of Commonwealth Financial Network told Forbes.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20  The stock market has set new highs during the impeachment proceedings, and consumer confidence is also climbing, CNBC reports.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 More: Mr. Trump brushed off the news at a campaign rally yesterday: \'93It doesn\'92t really feel like we\'92re being impeached,\'94 he said. Speaker Nancy Pelosi suggested that she might       \'a0    delay sending the articles to the Senate as leverage for negotiations on the rules for a trial. How TV       \'a0    covered the moment of impeachment vote. 
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Obamacare insurance mandate is struck down
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 A federal appeals court yesterday struck down the provision of the Affordable Care Act that requires Americans to have health insurance, saying it was unconstitutional, but the future of the decade-old health care law is still in limbo, writes the NYT\'92s Abby Goodnough.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The decision did not invalidate the rest of the law, and the panel of the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit in New Orleans sent the case back to a federal district judge in Texas to see which parts of the law could survive without the mandate.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 If the law were thrown out, insurers would no longer have to cover people up to age 26 on their parents\'92 plans, and could refuse coverage for more than 50 million people with pre-existing conditions. About 17 million Americans bought coverage through the A.C.A.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The case could go before the Supreme Court. The California attorney general, Xavier Becerra, said he planned to petition the court to hear the case. He led 21 states that intervened to try to preserve the law.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 President Trump, who campaigned on repealing the law, tried to appeal to both opponents of the law and people concerned about losing their health insurance.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 He called the ruling \'93a big win for all Americans,\'94 and said it would not alter the health care system. Mr. Trump also said he wanted to protect people with pre-existing conditions.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The case is unlikely to be resolved before next year\'92s presidential election.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Leaked Bank of England feed gave investors an edge
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The Bank of England said today that an audio feed from its news conferences had been leaked to some investors before it was made public. The early access to policymakers\'92 remarks gave those investors a leg up on the rest of the market, reports the NYT\'92s Amie Tsang.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The central bank is investigating the source of the leak, an unidentified third-party supplier that has provided sound from news conferences ahead of their video feed since earlier this year.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Investors closely monitor the news conferences to gain insight. \'93In the world of high-speed trading, just a few seconds\'92 lead time can offer some investors a trading advantage,\'94 Ms. Tsang reports.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The bank said it had disabled the supplier\'92s access. \'93The bank operates the highest standards of information security around the release of the market-sensitive decisions of its policy committees,\'94 it said.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Uber reaches a settlement on sexual harassment
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Uber has a resolution on one investigation into its workplace culture: Yesterday, the ride-hailing company agreed to create a $4.4 million fund to compensate employees who had been sexually harassed at work, the NYT\'92s Kate Conger writes.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The company \'93permitted a culture of sexual harassment and retaliation,\'94 the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission found. It has been examining workplace issues there since 2017.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Besides creating the fund, the company agreed to three years of monitoring by a former agency commissioner to ensure that it changes its practices.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 \'93This agreement will hopefully empower women in technology to speak up against sexism in the workplace knowing that their voices can yield meaningful change,\'94 a lawyer for the Commission said.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The prevalence of sexual harassment at Uber came to light when a former engineer, Susan Fowler, published an essay describing how the company had allowed inappropriate behavior to fester.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The company has \'93worked hard to ensure that all employees can thrive at Uber by putting fairness and accountability at the heart of who we are and what we do,\'94 said Tony West, the company\'92s chief legal officer.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 A big threat to job growth: demographics
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The U.S. job market continues to exceed expectations, but it is on a collision course with a dimming demographic outlook, writes Greg Ip in the WSJ.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Job numbers are growing faster than expected: The current economic expansion has lasted a record 10-plus years. But the U.S. population is smaller than the Census Bureau had predicted.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 \'93The U.S. has had two longstanding demographic advantages over other countries: higher fertility and immigration,\'94 Mr. Ip writes. \'93Both are eroding.\'94
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20  The country\'92s fertility rate dropped to its lowest on record in 2018.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20  And the foreign-born population in the U.S. had a historically low expansion rate last year.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 \'93Job creation is constrained by the number of people of working age,\'94 Mr. Ip writes. And until the trends are reversed, \'93the U.S. cannot assume it is immune to the demographic downdraft holding back Germany and Japan.\'94
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Boeing suppliers wait for the other shoe to drop
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Boeing buys parts from 600 suppliers around the world to build its 737 Max planes. Those suppliers are now waiting to see how the company\'92s temporary halt in production will affect their businesses, writes the NYT\'92s David Yaffe-Bellany.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 \'93We are in a crisis mode,\'94 Philippe, the C.E.O. of Safran, a French company that makes engines for the Max in partnership with General Electric, told L\'92usine nouvelle, a French newspaper. \'93Any day we do nothing now costs us money.\'94
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The grounding of the Max has reduced G.E.\'92s  cash flow by $400 million per quarter, company officials said in August. And Spirit AeroSystems, a Kansas company that manufactures the plane\'92s fuselage, relies on Boeing for 80 percent of its revenue.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Yet \'93the full reach of Boeing\'92s production process extends beyond those direct suppliers,\'94 Mr. Yaffe-Bellany writes.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Major suppliers that also manufacture materials for other companies may be equipped to weather the suspension, while smaller operations will struggle. Yet a halt to production that lasts longer than a month could put even those larger companies in peril.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 More: President Trump reportedly called Boeing\'92s C.E.O. on Sunday to discuss the company\'92s plans to halt production of the 737 Max. 
