\f3\fs20 How to Keep Private Data Private
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 New revelations seem to emerge every month or so about privacy violations by the internet\'92s biggest platforms. With concerns over online privacy increasing, United States regulators and lawmakers are scrambling to create laws and regulations to protect internet users.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The result so far has amounted to a fractured and often dizzying regulatory landscape for businesses trying to navigate the limits of their ability to collect, share and protect user data.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 It has been a striking turn of events for Silicon Valley, which Democrats and Republicans had for years sought to bolster by limiting laws that could curb the growth of America\'92s brightest engine of economic growth. But with Europe\'92s implementation last year of a privacy law known as the General Data Protection Regulation and issues like Facebook\'92s mishandling of data harvested by the political consulting firm Cambridge Analytica, the question for lawmakers is not whether to regulate, but how forcefully.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Members of Congress have promised a new comprehensive federal privacy law to keep in step with Europe\'92s groundbreaking law. There are even state and federal proposals to put a price on the value of personal data, and internet companies would have to pay users in order to profit from their information. CECILIA KANG
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Recommendations
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 PASS A COMPREHENSIVE FEDERAL LAW The law would pre-empt (or nullify) one in California that is about to go into place, because the existence of state and federal laws creates a confusing regulatory landscape. This federal law must create baseline standards on the kind of data collection companies can pursue.
\f0\fs24 \

