\f3\fs20 \cf0 It was election night at La Boom, a Queens nightclub, and Tiffany Cab\'e1n\'92s supporters had something to say.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 \'93Black Lives Matter!\'94 they shouted, an extraordinary cry at the victory party for a district attorney candidate. \'93Black Lives Matter!\'94 
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Such was the scene as the night\'92s tally ended with Ms. Cab\'e1n 1,090 votes ahead of Borough President Melinda Katz in the Democratic primary. The final toll won\'92t be known until at least next week, when absentee and other paper ballots are counted.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 If Ms. Cab\'e1n\'92s lead holds, New York is likely to be added to the list of cities that have elected district attorneys who want to remake the criminal justice system to undo two decades of policies that led to the imprisonment of hundreds of thousands of black and Latino Americans, too often for minor crimes and drug-related offenses.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The election also affirms the growing power of a fairly new force in New York politics: a millennial-based coalition pulling the Democratic Party to the left, and challenging its leadership machine.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 When Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez beat Joseph Crowley, the Queens Democratic chairman and fourth-ranking House member, last June, she gained star power more akin to Beyonc\'e9\'92s than that of a freshman member of Congress. The city\'92s political establishment thought it was a fluke.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Victories by reform Democrats in the New York State Senate primary elections in September threw shade on those doubts. This election should put to rest the idea that the coalition isn\'92t a sustainable force.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Conventional wisdom would have suggested that Tuesday\'92s election results were impossible. Months ago, few had ever heard of Ms. Cab\'e1n, a 31-year-old public defender with seven years\'92 experience. In her way stood the entirety of the county Democratic organization backing Ms. Katz, a longtime player in Queens politics. Powerful unions pledged to support Ms. Katz; the real estate industry provided plentiful donations. Gov. Andrew Cuomo endorsed her. So did prominent African-American elected officials like Representative Gregory Meeks, Mr. Crowley\'92s successor as head of the Queens County Democrats, who moved to get out black voters in southeast Queens.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Their ads and allies warned that Ms. Cab\'e1n\'92s inexperience and radical ideas would endanger people\'92s safety. 
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 But in the end, Ms. Cab\'e1n\'92s message proved more compelling to her supporters than those warnings were to everyone else. 
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 With the help of the Working Families Party and her fellow Democratic Socialists of America, she has shocked the state\'92s Democratic establishment, no matter the final outcome.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Who are these usurpers? Many are part of a generation still quite young when the crack epidemic swept the city in the 1980s and \'9290s, but whose political consciousness was forged by the consequences of the brutal reaction to that era: decades of over-policing that criminalized blacks and Latinos. 
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 It\'92s a generation that feels that the Democratic Party leadership has failed it, not only on criminal justice, but on issues from inequality to immigration to the Iraq war.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 I am one of them. Many of us are highly educated, but struggle to get ahead after years of stagnant wages, student loans and rents that just keep going up. To these voters, the real estate money helping fuel Ms. Katz\'92s campaign probably didn\'92t help her case.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 We talk openly about sexual harassment. We speak about gender and sexual orientation in fluid terms that even the most well intentioned in our parents\'92 generation struggle to understand. If we are not immigrants ourselves, we\'92re likely to be welcoming to them. 
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Ms. Cab\'e1n describes herself as a \'93queer Latina.\'94 Her parents grew up in public housing. She  went on to graduate from Pennsylvania State University and New York Law School.
\f0\fs24 \

