\f3\fs20 \cf0 Last month, Jessica Cisneros, a 26-year-old native of South Texas and immigration lawyer, announced her primary challenge against Representative Henry Cuellar, a Democrat who represents Texas\'92s 28th District. Just five years ago, Ms. Cisneros worked as an intern in Washington for Mr. Cuellar, whom she now refers to as \'93Trump\'92s favorite Democrat.\'94 
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 With the help of Justice Democrats, which supported Representatives Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez and Ayanna Pressley in their successful bids to oust longtime Democratic incumbents last year, Ms. Cisneros raised more than $100,000 in the first 48 hours of her campaign, she said. Since then, she has raised $47,000 more, with donations averaging about $23. 
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Mr. Cuellar, an eight-term congressman who won in 2018 with 84 percent of the vote, stood with moderate Democrats and Republicans last week in approving a $4.6 billion emergency aid package for border states without the restrictions sought by the Congressional Hispanic Caucus and others. Ms. Cisneros said his vote offered \'93a blank check to Trump and the Republicans\'92 anti-immigrant agenda.\'94
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 As controversies continue to surround immigrant detention centers, Ms. Cisneros has made Mr. Cuellar\'92s donations from companies that run the centers and private prisons a central issue of her campaign.  Since he was first elected to Congress in 2004, Mr. Cuellar has received donations from the Koch brothers, been given an \'93A\'94 rating by the National Rifle Association and co-sponsored anti-abortion legislation, prompting criticism from some Democrats. 
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Ms. Cisneros was the first of two primary challengers to be endorsed by Justice Democrats so far this cycle. Jamaal Bowman, a school principal from the Bronx running against a 16-term incumbent, was the second.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 If she wins, Ms. Cisneros would be the youngest woman ever elected to Congress. She is just one year older than the minimum age required to run, a fact she considers an asset. Like some other liberal Democrats, she supports the idea of free public college, and she is still paying off six-figure loans from law school at the University of Texas at Austin. 
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 We spoke to Ms. Cisneros about her background and campaign to represent the 28th District, which stretches from south of San Antonio down to the border. The interview has been edited and condensed for clarity.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Q: You grew up along the border in Laredo, Tex., and are a child of Mexican immigrants. How did that shape your political views?
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 A: My parents came from Nuevo Laredo, just across the bridge. I can see the Mexican side of the border right now, while I\'92m sitting at a friend\'92s house. 
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 When I was 7, I would see families crossing, and I would see that they were terrified. I didn\'92t know what it was, but felt like something was wrong. I felt kind of powerless \'97 I couldn\'92t spot the differences between their families and ours in what they experienced. 
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 At that point I committed that one day I was going to be an abogada. I felt like all my experiences were leading me to be an immigration lawyer. The culture down here is that everyone is bilingual \'97 the default is Spanish.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 My family came here because my sister had a medical issue. We were just like other Latino families I always saw. My parents sacrificed so much just for their kids to be happy here. Having that shared experience of growing up here, on two sides of the border, led me to think constantly about what immigrants experience.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 So you were convinced you wanted to be a lawyer, but how did you decide that you wanted to run for office? 
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Back in 2011, when I was in college at University of Texas at Austin, the debate around immigration wasn\'92t as heated as it is now. Under the Obama administration, we saw him as deporter in chief. He also brought back family detention. At UT, law students and professors were definitely focused on trying to end family detention.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Most of the debate as we see it now started once I was in law school. When Trump was elected, I was in my second year. I knew I wanted to do immigration law, so in the fall of 2016, I signed up for as many human rights law classes as I could. We were asking ourselves: Where are we going? What are going to be the asks for the next administration? We thought, why stop at ending family detention? Let\'92s push for the end of detention, period.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Then Trump gets elected and our ideas went from being on the offensive \'97 as in, what are we going to ask for? \'97 to being on major defense. How are we going to protect what we fought for? How will we help our clients and their rights when there are family separations and children dying in custody? 
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 How did you see the debate around immigration as a college student?
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 DACA came around 2012, and it wasn\'92t so much that it was all peace and tranquillity in my circles. I hung out with a lot of other Latina women, many of whom were undocumented or had parents who were. We didn\'92t really think this was a big celebration. It was more like, awesome, of course, this is the way it should be. This is the way it should work \'97 you are American, you just don\'92t have the paperwork.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 And what was your experience when you first started working as a lawyer?
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 I started as a lawyer doing a fellowship. The people I was representing were detained as their cases go through the immigration system. I thought: Finally, this is what I have been waiting for. I was so ready to use that experience to help people who look like me and my parents. 
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Then I began facing the cold reality that it doesn\'92t matter how great a case you present. I would have stacks and stacks of evidence as to why this person deserves asylum, because they face the real possibility of death if they go back. But the laws just aren\'92t there yet. You have to be pigeonholed in a certain category to say, yes, you are going to get killed, to get asylum. That\'92s just how nonsensical our laws are. 
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 I realized that if the laws are the problem, then I am going to have to go to Congress to fix that.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 You interned with the lawmaker you are now running against, Henry Cuellar. He was one of the first members of Congress liberal Democrats identified as a target for 2020. What was the internship like?
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 When I started, I was very, very excited, because I thought it would be a great insight to the legislative process, and maybe it would be an effective way to serve my people. 
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Once I got there, I noticed his silence on a lot of things I care about: women\'92s rights, poverty, health care. People I know with diabetes have to go to Nuevo Laredo for medications because it\'92s so expensive.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 He knew I was from the district. Never once did he come up to me and say: \'93What do you think I should be doing?\'94 
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 He is from here, yet he is getting money from private prisons and immigrant detention centers. That is going to be a big part of our campaign. Because he has not had a primary since 2006, his record hasn\'92t been an issue. There\'92s a lot he has never had to justify before this.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 When you first announced your campaign, several people compared you to Representative Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez, who defeated a longtime incumbent in a Democratic primary. What did you think of that comparison?
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 People think because I am a young Latina who is trying to help the Democratic Party I am just like her. I have a lot of admiration for her, but that doesn\'92t mean we\'92re the same. I am trying to be the first Jessica Cisneros, and just do that well.
\f0\fs24 \

