\f3\fs20 \cf0 I\'92m struck at how many people have come up to me recently and said, \'93Trump\'92s going to get re-elected, isn\'92t he?\'94 And in each case, when I drilled down to ask why, I bumped into the Democratic presidential debates in June. I think a lot of Americans were shocked by some of the things they heard there. I was.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 I was shocked that so many candidates in the party whose nominee I was planning to support want to get rid of the private health insurance covering some 250 million Americans and have \'93Medicare for all\'94 instead. I think we should strengthen Obamacare and eventually add a public option.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 I was shocked that so many were ready to decriminalize illegal entry into our country. I think people should have to ring the doorbell before they enter my house or my country. 
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 I was shocked at all those hands raised in support of providing comprehensive health coverage to undocumented immigrants. I think promises we\'92ve made to our fellow Americans should take priority, like to veterans in need of better health care.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 And I was shocked by how feeble was front-runner Joe Biden\'92s response to the attack from Kamala Harris \'97 and to the more extreme ideas promoted by those to his left.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 So, I wasn\'92t surprised to hear so many people expressing fear that the racist, divisive, climate-change-denying, woman-abusing jerk who is our president was going to get re-elected, and was even seeing his poll numbers rise.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Dear Democrats: This is not complicated! Just nominate a decent, sane person, one committed to reunifying the country and creating more good jobs, a person who can gain the support of the independents, moderate Republicans and suburban women who abandoned Donald Trump in the midterms and thus swung the House of Representatives to the Democrats and could do the same for the presidency. And that candidate can win!
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 But please, spare me the revolution! It can wait. Win the presidency, hold the House and narrow the spread in the Senate, and a lot of good things still can be accomplished. \'93No,\'94 you say, \'93the left wants a revolution now!\'94 O.K., I\'92ll give the left a revolution now: four more years of Donald Trump.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 That will be a revolution.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Four years of Trump feeling validated in all the crazy stuff he\'92s done and said. Four years of Trump unburdened by the need to run for re-election and able to amplify his racism, make Ivanka secretary of state, appoint even more crackpots to his cabinet and likely get to name two right-wing Supreme Court justices under the age of 40.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Yes sir, that will be a revolution!
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 It will be an overthrow of all the norms, values, rules and institutions that we cherish, that made us who we are and that have united us in this common project called the United States of America.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 If the fear of that doesn\'92t motivate the Democratic Party\'92s base, then shame on those people. Not all elections are equal. Some elections are a vote for great changes \'97 like the Great Society. Others are a vote to save the country. This election is the latter.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 That doesn\'92t mean a Democratic candidate should stand for nothing, just keep it simple: Focus on building national unity and good jobs.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 I say national unity because many Americans are terrified and troubled by how bitterly divided, and therefore paralyzed, the country has become. There is an opening for a unifier. 
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 And I say good jobs because when the wealth of the top 1 percent equals that of the bottom 90 percent, we do have to redivide the pie. I favor raising taxes on the wealthiest Americans to subsidize universal pre-K education and to reduce the burden of student loans. Let\'92s give kids a head start and college grads a fresh start.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 But I\'92m disturbed that so few of the Democratic candidates don\'92t also talk about growing the pie, let alone celebrating American entrepreneurs and risk-takers. Where do they think jobs come from?
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The winning message is to double down on redividing the pie in ways that give everyone an opportunity for a slice while also growing the pie sustainably. 
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Trump is growing the pie by cannibalizing the future. He is creating a growth spurt by building up enormous financial and carbon debts that our kids will pay for.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Democrats should focus on how we create sustainable wealth and good jobs, which is the American public-private partnership model: Government enriches the soil and entrepreneurs grow the companies.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 It has always been what\'92s made us rich, and we\'92ve drifted away from it: investing in quality education and basic scientific research; promulgating the right laws and regulations to incentivize risk-taking and prevent recklessness and monopolies that can cripple free markets; encouraging legal immigration of both high-energy and high-I.Q. foreigners; and building the world\'92s best enabling infrastructure \'97 ports, roads, bandwidth and basic social safety nets.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Ask Gina Raimondo, Rhode Island\'92s governor, and my kind of Democrat. She was just elected in 2018 for a second term. In both her elections she had to win a primary against a more-left Democrat. When Raimondo took office in 2015, Rhode Island had unemployment near 7 percent, and over 20 percent in some of the building trades.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 \'93When I ran in 2014, there was a temptation to appeal to particular constituencies \'97 gun safety, choice, all things that I believe in,\'94 Raimondo recalled. \'93I resisted that temptation because I felt the single greatest issue was economic insecurity and people who were afraid they were never going to get a job. So I said there are not three or four issues, there\'92s one issue: jobs.\'94 Unemployment in Rhode Island today is about 3.6 percent.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Raimondo has faced a constant refrain from critics on her left that she is too close to business. \'93I created an incentive program for companies to get a tax subsidy if they created jobs that pay above our state\'92s median income or jobs in advanced industries,\'94 she noted. \'93I have cut small-business taxes two years in a row since 2015. I am not ashamed of any of that.\'94
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Because, she continued, \'93I listen to people every day, and you hear what they are worried about. People say to me, \'91Governor, I just got a real job.\'92 And I\'92d ask them, \'91What is a real job?\'92 And they\'92d say, \'91It\'92s a job where I can support my family with real benefits.\'92 So I named our state job-training program \'91Real Jobs Rhode Island.\'92\'94 It will be impossible to \'93sustain a vibrant democracy with this level of inequality.\'94
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The right answer is to reinvigorate the key elements of a healthy public-private partnership, said Raimondo: higher taxes on wealthier people, more investments in affordable housing, infrastructure and universal pre-K, and empowering the private sector to create more real jobs \'97 \'93so that no one who is working full time at any job should have to collect Medicaid and need food stamps to make ends meet.\'94
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Concluded Raimondo: \'93I am no apologist for a brand of capitalism that leads to unsustainable inequality. But I do believe a more responsible capitalism is necessary for growth. We need to redivide the pie and grow the pie. I am a \'91pro-growth Democrat.\'92 I am for growing the pie as long as everyone has a shot at getting their slice.\'94
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 That\'92s a simple message that can connect with enough Democrats \'97 as well as independents, moderate Republicans and suburban women \'97 to win the White House.
