Voters of color could determine the results of the 2020 presidential election. In the primaries, African-Americans constitute a large share of Democrats in the early-voting state of South Carolina and on Super Tuesday, when many other states vote. In the general election, the path to the presidency for a Democrat will depend in part on turning out large numbers of people of color in Southern states (North Carolina, Virginia, possibly Florida) and also in the Rust Belt, where the post-Obama dip in turnout among African-Americans contributed to Hillary Clinton\'92s squeaker losses in Wisconsin and Pennsylvania.\
Warren has work to do to persuade people of color to support her. In the last couple of Democratic primaries, these voters started out favoring candidates who they thought would be most likely to win, not those who were the most liberal. Black voters backed Hillary Clinton in 2008 until they were sure Barack Obama had enough support to beat her, and in 2016 they stuck with her over Bernie Sanders. This time, they have black candidates \'97 Kamala Harris, Cory Booker and Wayne Messam \'97 to choose from. And voters of color may be skeptical of Warren\'92s vision of class solidarity transcending racial division. As it turned out, Warren\'92s case that most white people voted for Trump because of economic distress, and \'93despite the hate,\'94 as she said right after the election, didn\'92t really hold up. A study published last year found that among white voters, perceived racial or global threats explained their shift toward Trump better than financial concerns did. What does that say about the chances of winning as a liberal who tries to take the racism out of populism?\
When Warren makes the case about what needs to change in America by leaning on the period from 1935 to 1980, she\'92s talking about a time of greater economic equality \'97 but also a period when people of color were excluded from the benefits of government policies that buoyed the white middle class. In a video announcing that she was exploring a presidential bid, Warren acknowledged that history by saying that families of color today face \'93a path made even harder by generations of discrimination.\'94 For example, the federal agency created during the New Deal drew red lines around mostly black neighborhoods on maps to deny mortgage loans to people who lived in them.\
Warren spoke about this problem years before she went into politics. Redlining contributed to the racial wealth gap, and that had consequences Warren saw in her bankruptcy studies \'97 black families were more vulnerable to financial collapse. Their vulnerability was further heightened by subprime and predatory lending. In \'93The Two-Income Trap,\'94 Warren called these kinds of loans \'93legally sanctioned corporate plans to steal from minorities.\'94\
In March, Warren took a three-day trip to the South. She started on a Sunday afternoon, with a town hall \'97 one of 101 she has done across the country \'97 at a high school in a mostly black neighborhood in Memphis. It\'92s her format of choice; the questions she fields help sharpen her message. The local politicians who showed up that day were African-American, but most of the crowd was white.\
The next morning, Warren drove to the Mississippi Delta. Her husband, Mann, was on spring break from teaching and along for the trip. Warren\'92s staff welcomes his presence because Warren loves having him with her and because he\'92s willing to chat up voters (who often call him \'93Mr. Warren\'94). In the small town of Cleveland, Miss., Warren sprang out of her black minivan in the parking lot of a church to shake the hand of an African-American state senator, Willie Simmons. They were meeting for the first time: He had agreed to take her on a walking tour after her campaign got in touch and said she wanted to learn about housing in the Delta.\
Simmons and Warren set off down a block of modest ranch houses, some freshly painted, others peeling, preceded by TV crews and trailed by the rest of the press as her aides darted in to keep us out of the shot. The scrum made conversation stagy, but Simmons gradually eased into answering Warren\'92s questions. He pointed out cracks in the foundations of some houses; the lack of money to repair old buildings was a problem in the Delta. They stopped at a vacant lot. The neighbors wanted to turn it into a playground, but there was no money for that either.\
Warren nodded and then took a stab at communicating her ideas to the local viewers who might catch a few of her words that night. She hit the highlights of the affordable housing bill she released in the Senate months earlier \'97 3.2 million new homes over 10 years, an increase in supply that Moody\'92s estimated would reduce projected rents by 10 percent. When the tour ended, Simmons told the assembled reporters that he didn\'92t know whom he would support for president, but Warren got points for showing up and being easy to talk to \'97 \'93touchable,\'94 he said.\
That night, Warren did a CNN town hall at Jackson State University, the third historically black college she has visited this year. Warren moved toward the audience at the first opportunity, walking past the chair placed for her onstage. She laid out the basics of her housing bill, stressing that it addressed the effects of discrimination. \'93Not just a passive discrimination,\'94 Warren said. \'93Realize that into the 1960s in America, the federal government was subsidizing the purchase of homes for white families and discriminating against black families.\'94 Her bill included funds to help people from redlined areas, or who had been harmed by subprime loans, buy houses. The audience applauded.\
Warren also said that night that she supported a \'93national full-blown conversation\'94 about reparations for slavery and Jim Crow. She saw this as a necessary response to the stark wealth gap between black and white families. \'93Today in America \'97 because of housing discrimination, because of employment discrimination \'97 we live in a world where the average white family has $100 and the average black family has about $5.\'94 Several Democratic candidates have said they support a commission to study reparations. Ta-Nehisi Coates, author of the influential 2014 Atlantic article \'93The Case for Reparations,\'94 said in a recent interview with The New Yorker that Warren was the candidate whose commitment seemed real because she had asked him to talk with her about his article when it came out years ago. \'93She was deeply serious,\'94 Coates said.\
Warren is often serious and doesn\'92t hesitate to convey her moral outrage. \'93I\'92ll own it,\'94 she told me about her anger. She talked about women expressing to her their distress about sexual harassment and assault. \'93Well, yeah,\'94 Warren said. \'93No kidding that a woman might be angry about that. Women have a right to be angry about being treated badly.\'94\
Trump gets angry all the time; whether a woman can do the same and win remains a question. Warren\'92s campaign is simultaneously working in another register. On Twitter, it has been posting videos of Warren calling donors who have given as little as $3. They can\'92t believe it\'92s her. When the comedian and actress Ashley Nicole Black tweeted, \'93Do you think Elizabeth Warren has a plan to fix my love life?\'94 Warren tweeted back and then called Black, who finished the exchange with a fan-girl note: \'93Guess who\'92s crying and shaking and just talked to Elizabeth Warren on the phone?!?!? We have a plan to get my mom grandkids, it\'92s very comprehensive, and it does involve raising taxes on billionaires.\'94\
After Trump\'92s election, Warren and Sanders said that if Trump followed through on his promise to rebuild the economy for workers and their families, they would help. If Trump had championed labor over corporations, he could have scrambled American politics by creating new alliances. But that version of his presidency didn\'92t come to pass. Instead, by waging trade wars that hurt farm states and manufacturing regions more than the rest of the country, Trump has punished his base economically (even if they take satisfaction in his irreverence and his judicial appointments).\
Warren has been speaking to those voters. In June, she put out an \'93economic patriotism\'94 plan filled with ideas about helping American industries. By stepping into the vacuum for economic populism the president has left, Warren forced a reckoning on Fox News, Trump\'92s safe space on TV, from the host Tucker Carlson. Usually a Trump loyalist, he has recently styled himself a voice for the white working class.\
Carlson opened his show by using more than two minutes of airtime to quote Warren\'92s analysis of how giant American companies are abandoning American workers. Carlson has warned that immigrants make the country \'93poorer and dirtier\'94 and laced his show with racism, but now he told his mostly Republican viewers: \'93Ask yourself, what part of the statement you just heard did you disagree with?\'94 He continued, \'93Here\'92s the depressing part: Nobody you voted for said that or would ever say it.\'94 The next day, a new conservative Never Trump website called The Bulwark ran a long and respectful essay called \'93Why Elizabeth Warren Matters.\'94\
A month earlier in Mingo County, W.Va., where more than 80 percent of voters cast a ballot for Trump, Warren went to a local fire station to talk about her plan for addressing the opioid crisis. It\'92s big: She wants to spend $100 billion over 10 years, including $50 million annually for West Virginia, the state with the highest rate of deaths from drug overdoses. In Trump\'92s latest budget, he has requested an increase of $1.5 billion to respond directly to the epidemic. Against a backdrop of firefighters\'92 coats hanging in cinder-block cubbies, Warren moved among a crowd of about 150. Many hands went up when she asked who knew someone struggling with opioids. She brought up the role of \'93corporations that made big money off getting people addicted and keeping them addicted.\'94 People with \'93Make America Great Again\'94 stickers       \'a0    nodded and clapped, according to Politico.\
If Warren competes for rural voters in the general election (if not to win a red state then to peel off enough of them to make a difference in a purple one), her strong support for abortion rights and gun control will stand in her way. Lately, she has framed her argument for keeping abortion clinics open in economic terms, too. \'93Women of means will still have access to abortions,\'94 she said at a town hall on MSNBC hosted by Chris Hayes of the effects of new state laws aimed at closing clinics. \'93Who won\'92t will be poor women, will be working women, will be women who can\'92t afford to take off three days from work, will be very young women.\'94 She finished by saying, \'93We do not pass laws that take away that freedom from the women who are most vulnerable.\'94\
Biden and Sanders have been polling better with non-college-educated white voters than Warren has. David Axelrod, the former Obama strategist and political commentator, thinks that even if her ideas resonate, she has yet to master the challenge of communicating with this group. \'93She\'92s lecturing,\'94 he said. \'93There\'92s a lot of resistance, because people feel like she\'92s talking down to them.\'94\
Warren didn\'92t sound to me like a law professor on the trail, but she did sound like a teacher. Trying to educate people isn\'92t the easiest way to connect with them. \'93Maybe she could bring it down a level,\'94 Lola Sewell, a community organizer in Selma, Ala., suggested. \'93A lot of us aren\'92t involved with Wall Street and those places.\'94\
Warren may also confront a double bind for professional women: To command respect, they have to prove that they\'92re experts, but once they do, they\'92re often seen as less likable. At one point, I asked Warren whether there was anything good about running for president as a woman. \'93It is what it is,\'94 she said.\
When I first talked with Warren in February, when her poll numbers were low, I wondered whether she was content with simply forcing Democratic candidates to engage with her ideas. During the 2016 primaries, when Warren did not endorse Sanders, she wanted influence over Hillary Clinton\'92s economic appointments should she win the presidency. Cleaving the Democratic administration from Wall Street \'97 that was enough at the time. She could make a similar decision in 2020 or try to get her own appointment. If Warren became Treasury secretary, she could resuscitate the Consumer Financial Protection Bureau, which Trump has worked to declaw, and tip all kinds of decisions away from banks and toward the families who come to her town halls and tell her about the loans they can\'92t pay.\
By mid-June, however, when I went to Washington to talk to Warren for the last time, she was very much in the race. New polls showed her in second place in California and Nevada. She had more to lose, and perhaps as a result, her answers were more scripted, more like her speeches.\
Warren, like everyone in the race, has yet to prove that she has the political skills and broad-enough support to become president. But a parallel from another country suggests that perhaps bearing down on policy is the best strategy against right-wing populism. Luigi Zingales, the University of Chicago economist, comes from Italy, and he feared Trump\'92s rise back in 2011, having watched the ascension of Silvio Berlusconi, the corrupt billionaire tycoon who was elected prime minister of Italy in the 2000s as a right-wing populist. After Trump\'92s victory in 2016, Zingales pointed out in a New York Times Op-Ed that the two candidates who defeated Berlusconi treated him as \'93an ordinary opponent,\'94 focusing on policy issues rather than his character. \'93The Democratic Party should learn this lesson,\'94 Zingales wrote. He now thinks that Warren is positioned to mount that kind of challenge. \'93I think so,\'94 he said, \'93if she does not fall for his provocations.\'94\
Warren and I met in her Washington apartment. The floor at the entrance had been damaged by a leak in the building, and the vacuum cleaner was standing next to the kitchen counter. I said I was a bit relieved by the slight disarray because her house in Cambridge was so supremely uncluttered, and she burst out laughing. She sat on the couch as we spoke about the indignities to come, the way in which her opponents \'97 Biden, Trump, who knew who else \'97 would try to make her unrecognizable to herself. What would she do about that? Warren leaned back and stretched her feet out, comfortable in gray wool socks. \'93The answer is, we\'92ve got time,\'94 she said. \'93I\'92ll just keep talking to people \'97 I like talking to people.\'94\
