\f3\fs20 \cf0 Hi. Welcome to On Politics, your guide to the day in national politics. I\'92m Lisa Lerer, your host.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 [Get On Politics delivered to your inbox.]
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Twenty-one candidates. Eighteen questions. Four months of reporting, traveling, editing and programming by a team of more than two dozen people.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The result: Meet the Candidates, a collection of video interviews with nearly everyone in the Democratic presidential primary race, covering topics both political and personal.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Today we\'92re turning over the top of the newsletter to my colleagues Alex Burns and Sydney Ember, the reporters who put together this amazing (and huge!) project, to reflect on their favorite moments and tell some behind-the-scenes stories.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 [See the whole project here \'97 you can browse it by question or by candidate.]
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Alex: Well, that was a lot of interviews! And videos. So many videos. You and I split the interviewing almost evenly (I think you did 11 and I did 10.) Was there anything that stood out the most to you \'97 that moment that just keeps popping into your head \'97 in terms of how the candidates answered questions or what they said?
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Sydney: My honest answer is the sheer volume of sighs that Bill de Blasio elicited when I asked him about his most recent embarrassing moment. They just kept coming!
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 [See Mr. de Blasio\'92s answer here.]
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Alex: O.K., but wearing cargo shorts to the gym is about as embarrassing as it gets, so \'97 understandable.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Sydney: I kept expecting something on a groundhog.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 I was also struck by how similar some of the candidates were on questions like whether they supported or opposed the death penalty (nearly all said they opposed it). But were there any big differences that stood out to you?
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 [See their answers on the death penalty here.]
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Alex: The death penalty question was really striking to me, too. Even Steve Bullock, the only candidate who said he favored it in some circumstances, essentially said he was against it for most of what we think of as capital crimes, like murder. The only hypothetical exception he named was terrorism.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Also, somewhat to my surprise, I think the interviews really showed some of the ways that the leftward lurch of the Democratic Party has been overstated. On the single-payer question, for instance, there was very little \'93Medicare for All or bust\'94 rhetoric. Even clearly liberal candidates \'97 like Elizabeth Warren, Kamala Harris and Cory Booker \'97 indicated they\'92d likely focus on improving the private health insurance system.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 [See their answers on health care here.]
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Sydney: Totally. That was surprising, especially since so many candidates talk on the trail about their support for \'93Medicare for All.\'94 One thing I really enjoyed was getting to learn more about the candidates as people. They so rarely talk candidly about themselves, but I thought some of their most revealing answers were to the personal questions we asked \'97 about their comfort food on the campaign trail, for instance, and about what they do to relax. We also got to spend a little bit of time with them before the interviews, an informal setting that was actually (at least for me) pretty unique.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 [See their answers on comfort food and       \'a0    how they relax.]
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Alex: Yes! Most of the interviews I did were at our office in New York, so it was fun to see how some of them handled being in the newsroom. Ms. Warren and Ms. Harris attracted pretty sizable crowds and handled it in pretty different ways \'97 Ms. Warren with a kind of impromptu mini-town hall about tech regulation, Ms. Harris by focusing on a very animated conversation with Sam Sifton, the food editor. (Other candidates were, ah, less recognized.)
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Sydney: At least one waved and \'85 no one waved back. I also got to travel a bit for some of the interviews I did (mostly to D.C., to be fair). But we met Beto O\'92Rourke at a sound stage in Austin. And we traveled to Cedar Rapids, Iowa, to interview Bernie Sanders.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Alex: I have to ask, what was it like to do that interview with Mr. Sanders after your rather contentious exchange with him back in May
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Sydney: You know, he was very pleasant! He answered all of our questions, including the personal ones that he is known to vehemently dislike. One of my favorite moments was when he started talking about his grandchildren. It was the most tender I\'92ve ever seen him.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 [See all of Mr. Sanders\'92s answers here.]
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Alex: That\'92s sweet. It was interesting to see which candidates were looser on the personal questions versus who seemed happier talking about policy. I kind of judge a number of the candidates who refused to name an actual most embarrassing recent moment, especially in contrast to someone like Amy Klobuchar, who delivered one involving an airplane and her underwear. That\'92s candor!
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 [See Ms. Klobuchar\'92s answer here.]
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 If you could go back and add one more question to the list, what do you think it would be? I saw someone on Twitter saying she wished we had asked about pets.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Sydney: I think I\'92d add a question on education (another topic I saw someone on Twitter suggest). Policies around student debt, but also universal pre-K and charter schools, have become something of a focus among candidates in recent months, and it would have been interesting to hear their answers side-by-side to a question like, \'93How would you improve the country\'92s education system?\'94
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Alex: That would have been good. We started the project before Ms. Warren\'92s student loan proposal really intensified that debate, and it\'92s now a pretty significant part of the race.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 I would love to have asked something about bipartisanship or their instincts about working with Republicans \'97 whether they think it\'92s possible, whether it would be a goal or something they\'92d do only grudgingly, whether they have to find partners on the other side to get stuff done or whether getting stuff done requires Democrats to be politically dominant. It\'92s such a dividing line in the field, and all the more so now that Joe Biden has decided to stake much of his campaign on the idea that he could make Republicans his partners in governing.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Of course, we wouldn\'92t have been able to ask Mr. Biden, since he did not show up!
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 ____________________
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 A timeline of the Biden controversy
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Joe Biden\'92s remarks this week on working with segregationists kicked off the biggest fight of the Democratic primary so far. For those who have not kept up, here\'92s a timeline of everything that has happened in the past 48 hours.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20  On Tuesday night, at a fund-raiser at the Carlyle Hotel in New York City, Mr. Biden invoked two former Democratic senators who were staunchly opposed to desegregation \'97 James O. Eastland and Herman E. Talmadge \'97 as he looked back fondly at the \'93civility\'94 of the Senate of the 1970s.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20  On Wednesday afternoon, Senator Cory Booker, one of two black candidates running for president, said Mr. Biden was \'93wrong\'94 to use segregationists as examples for bringing the country together and suggested he should issue an apology.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20  Other Democrats spoke up on Wednesday afternoon, too. Senator Kamala Harris, who is also black, said, \'93If those men had their way, I wouldn\'92t be in the United States Senate.\'94 Senators Bernie Sanders and Elizabeth Warren, Mayor Bill de Blasio and others also criticized the former vice president.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20  Before a fund-raiser on Wednesday evening, Mr. Biden was asked by reporters about his comments. \'93Apologize for what?\'94 he said. When a reporter mentioned that Mr. Booker had called for the apology, Mr. Biden shot back: \'93Cory should apologize. He knows better. There\'92s not a racist bone in my body.\'94
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20  Mr. Booker, in an interview on CNN Wednesday night, said that Mr. Biden \'93shouldn\'92t need this lesson.\'94
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20  At a fund-raiser later on Wednesday, Mr. Biden invoked the former senators again, but changed his tone. \'93We had to put up with the likes of like Jim Eastland and Hermy Talmadge and all those segregationists and all of that,\'94 he said. \'93We were able to beat them on everything they stood for.\'94
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20  Finally, as my colleague Reid Epstein and I reported today, Mr. Biden called Mr. Booker late Wednesday night to try to smooth over tensions. We were told the tone between the men was conciliatory.
\f0\fs24 \

