Mr. O\'92Rourke entered the Democratic primary race this past week with an aspirational pitch and a semi-improvisational tour of Iowa, with a Hawkeyes baseball cap and bilingual profanity on the stump, broadcasting his message of generational uplift and immediately thrusting age into the main currents of the 2020 race.\
The contenders leading in initial polls, Mr. Sanders and former Vice President       \'a0    Joseph R. Biden Jr., will be 79 and 78 by Inauguration Day 2021. President Trump will be 74.\
Yet as party activists begin to appraise the field, they are already grappling with whether to once again embrace a younger candidate who reflects the future or shrug off age and elevate a veteran politician who most clearly represents their simultaneous craving for undiluted liberalism and someone who can       \'a0    thwart Mr. Trump.\
If history is a guide, Mr. O\'92Rourke and other Democrats betting on a youthful appeal \'97 like Cory Booker, 49; Juli\'e1n Castro, 44; or Pete Buttigieg and Tulsi Gabbard, both 37 \'97 should have an advantage. Of the last five Democratic presidents, only Lyndon B. Johnson, who ascended to the job because of the assassination of a 46-year-old president, was older than 52 when he was first elected president. The roster of Democratic losers in modern times is littered with nominees who were neither young nor new to the political scene.\
[Check out the Democratic field with our candidate tracker.]\
But for many in the party, dedication to this critical component of past success \'97 putting forward a new face \'97 is being tested in the 2020 race by twin impulses: the devotion to Mr. Sanders among voters many decades younger than him, who share his belief that American society is rife with inequities that will not be solved by candidates like Mr. O\'92Rourke, and an overriding desire among Democrats to defeat a president they believe is a menace to democracy.\
Supporters of Mr. Sanders believe he offers transformational change \'97 the promise of not merely ousting President Trump but also remaking the country into a more just place \'97 and brings experience that would help him survive a general election and expand the electorate.\
At the same time, moderates in the party are tempted by Mr. Biden, wagering that the political equivalent of comfort food to America may prove the safest recipe.\
This combination of a primary electorate that is at once hungry for structural, even radical, reform and deeply nervous about nominating someone too callow to defeat Mr. Trump poses perhaps the most serious challenge to a candidate like Mr. O\'92Rourke. He shuns ideological labels, even chafing at \'93progressive\'94 in the past; often avoids being pinned down on policy; and has no experience in the crucible of presidential politics.\
\'93I know Bernie has a laid-out plan for Medicare and free tuition,\'94 said Austin Palmer, a 25-year-old South Carolinian who went to see Mr. Sanders vow political revolution Thursday night in North Charleston. \'93Beto has made some broad statements so far.\'94\
Mr. Palmer invoked the recent scandal involving parents committing bribery to get their children into elite colleges, shaking his head at what he sees as a rotten society that must be razed, not reformed. Yet he also indicated that he was most enthusiastic about Mr. Sanders because of the polls he recalls showing that the Democrats\'92 2016 runner-up would have defeated Mr. Trump.\
\'93I\'92m really concerned about being able to beat Trump,\'94 he said. \'93That\'92s my big worry.\'94\
Mr. O\'92Rourke has ample time to flesh out his agenda \'97 he spoke fondly, if not always specifically, this past week of \'93bold, progressive ideas\'94 \'97 and he enjoys considerable assets: a history of record-shattering online fund-raising, the appeal of celebrity in a country besotted by fame and a grip on the imagination of a party that loves to fall in love after his star-making-if-campaign-losing Senate race in Texas.\
But he is facing a 2020 campaign and election that differ considerably from when Democrats last rewarded a generational argument in a presidential race by nominating then-Senator Barack Obama.\
\'93There\'92s still a big part of the party that wants to fall in love, and there\'92s another part of the party that will settle for anything that will beat Trump,\'94 said Senator Christopher S. Murphy of Connecticut, at 45 the youngest Democratic senator. \'93I think that\'92s a real, daily tension in the party that\'92s going to play out in real time.\'94\
There could ultimately be a best-of-both-worlds solution \'97 \'93It just happened that in 2008 and 2012 we fell in love with the most electable candidate,\'94 Mr. Murphy recalled \'97 but like many Democrats, he could only guess for now.\
\'93I would generally make the case that the Democratic Party should always be nominating the next-generation candidate,\'94 he said, \'93except I\'92m not sure any of the old rules apply.\'94\
The evidence was conflicting at Mr. Sanders\'92s South Carolina rally on Thursday.\
As unfathomable as it may be to the moderate wing of the Democratic Party, many in attendance made the case for Mr. Sanders as much on his electability as his liberal platform.\
\'93I want to support someone who I think really has a chance of winning,\'94 said Brandon Greene, a 27-year-old student and pastor. \'93We can\'92t take a gamble on a new candidate.\'94\
And Tasha Horton, a 45-year-old real estate broker with college-age children who \'93love the Bern,\'94 allowed that her \'93love is for Kamala but strategically it\'92s either Bernie or Biden.\'94\
Ms. Horton, who went to the same church gymnasium recently to see Senator Kamala Harris, 54, added: \'93We have to think that way. You can\'92t think with your heart.\'94\
Yet even as Mr. Greene and Ms. Horton, who are both African-American, made the case for Mr. Sanders, the bulk of the audience reflected limits in his appeal: In a city where nearly half of the population is black, the rally attendees were overwhelmingly white. As a soloist sang gospel music that doubled as a filibuster for the tardy senator, some in the crowd noodled as if it were a Phish jam rather than an organ-backed hymn about joy coming in the morning.\
Many of the voters at the Sanders event said they were open to other candidates; they just wanted to hear \'93about specifics,\'94 as Mr. Greene put it, and be convinced that a younger alternative could prove viable.\
Still, as Mr. Sanders took the stage and thundered against economic inequality, excoriating the compensation packages of individual health care executives, the contrast between his unsparing indictment and comprehensive agenda and Mr. O\'92Rourke\'92s frequent generalities could not have been starker.\
\'93I want to do something that very few public figures will do, and I want to tell you exactly what justice means to me and I hope to you,\'94 the senator told his youthful, sign-waving charges.\
In Iowa, meanwhile, the newest candidate in the race was casting his political worldview as a kind of high-minded pragmatism, describing bipartisanship as a necessity during his six years in the House minority.\
\'93I made it my mission to ensure that the perfect never becomes the enemy of the good,\'94 Mr. O\'92Rourke said to cheers in Mount Pleasant, Iowa, boasting of a veterans\'92 health care measure signed into law by Mr. Trump.\
He frames his events as two-sided conversations, at times prodding voters to say how they might solve the challenges they cite. \'93Thoughts? Ideas? Suggestions? Advice?\'94 he asked high school students in Fort Madison.\
When pressed, by voters and reporters, for more details, Mr. O\'92Rourke has equivocated or vacillated on several policy questions. Asked about health care at the first of eight events on Thursday, Mr. O\'92Rourke steered clear of \'93Medicare for all,\'94 the progressive proposal he once endorsed without apparent reservation, calling more generally for a \'93guaranteed, high-quality\'94 system instead.\
\'93I think that\'92s one of the ways to ensure that we get to guaranteed, high-quality health care for every single American,\'94 he said of \'93Medicare for all\'94 in Washington, Iowa. \'93I\'92m no longer sure that that\'92s the fastest way to get there.\'94\
Asked at another event about reparations, a growing issue in the Democratic race, Mr. O\'92Rourke held forth for four minutes \'97 on John Lewis, Martin Luther King, the arc of systemic racism \'97 without answering the question of where he stood.\
But Mr. O\'92Rourke\'92s lack of detail does not dissuade his most ardent supporters. As with Mr. Obama\'92s, the Texan\'92s admirers are galvanized by a message that, with leadership that can bring people of good will together across party lines, a better day for the country awaits.\
\'93Trump appeals to the worst of America, candidates like Beto appeal to the best of America,\'94 said Representative Hakeem Jeffries of New York, 48, a Democratic leader who may become the first Generation X House speaker someday and has not backed anyone in the race.\
Across eastern Iowa, Mr. O\'92Rourke encountered many young people excited by his candidacy, arriving in T-shirts from his Senate race or, in one case, a customized \'93Betomania\'94 button featuring the candidate with a guitar.\
\'93Everything about him is an inspiration,\'94 said Angela Scott, 27, after meeting (and high-fiving) Mr. O\'92Rourke at a sub shop in Burlington, Iowa. \'93You can\'92t help but like that man.\'94\
In other moments, though, his audiences included a striking dichotomy: enchanted older voters, convinced that younger voters would flock to Mr. O\'92Rourke and rescue the party from Mr. Trump, and younger voters excited by someone else.\
As Mr. O\'92Rourke spoke in Mount Pleasant, standing on a cafe counter, a cluster of teenage fans of Mr. Sanders watched in the wings, curious about Mr. O\'92Rourke but unmoved by any suggestion that Mr. Sanders is not a man for the times.\
\'93That\'92s ageism,\'94 said Garrick Dodson, a self-described socialist progressive who will turn 18 next month. \'93I don\'92t have a problem voting for an old person I agree with more than a young person.\'94\
Mr. Dodson and his friends suggested that their elders underestimated the boiling anger of the teen and 20-something generation, aghast at what they see as their forebears\'92 indifference to climate change and student loan debt.\
\'93Gen Z, baby,\'94 Mr. Dodson said.\
\'93Gen Z is coming,\'94 warned a peer, Madison Brady, 18. \'93We\'92re so angry.\'94\
