When the mike was passed around for audience questions, the first comment came from a retired nurse, an African-American woman who was worried that the Democrats were presenting too many choices to voters, and thus diluting their power. She wanted to win in 2020.\
\'93As a 63-year-old middle class female, I want to make a note to the Democrats,\'94 she said. \'93It is getting to be too much. We are getting too divided. Divided we will fall. Together we will stand.\'94\
Later, Mr. O\'92Rourke spoke of the historic injustices perpetrated against black people, from slavery to racist \'93redlining\'94 that denied them home loans.\
\'93I\'92m a white man who\'92s had a privilege in my life; I\'92m not enduring any one of those things that I\'92ve just described,\'94 he said. \'93But I\'92ve listened to those who have.\'94\
Watching in the back of the crowd were Kadara and Kaywon Nelson, a black couple in their 30s, who had come out to learn more about Mr. O\'92Rourke. They were anti-Trump, but otherwise undecided. The biggest issue for Ms. Nelson, the campus safety compliance officer, was the cost of health care.\
\'93And student loan debt,\'94 said Mr. Nelson, who works for a pharmaceutical company. \'93I don\'92t care about the wall.\'94\
They both said a candidate who could address the country\'92s issues was more important than finding one who represented their race. Mr. Nelson made reference to the political themes of the first Obama candidacy.\
\'93I think we\'92re past that,\'94 he said. \'93The message has got to be a little stronger, because \'91hope\'92 hasn\'92t gotten us much.\'94\
After the presentation, Dr. Tamara J. Jackson, the vice president of student affairs at South Carolina State, said she liked what she heard \'97 particularly Mr. O\'92Rourke\'92s emphasis on gay rights and ensuring H.B.C.U. funding.\
She was also impressed, she said, with Mr. Booker and Ms. Harris.\
\'93I\'92d like to see a black female as president,\'94 she said, \'93But I\'92m not sure America is ready.\'94\
She added: \'93I pray that I\'92m wrong about that.\'94\
